aracteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Caseborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Casbolt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Casbolt","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>casbalde</i> ‘bald head’, apparently a term of reproach: ‘Go home, casbalde with þi clowte’ (about 1440  <i>York Plays</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas De Caseborne II was born about 1374, in Cheriton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas De Caseborne I, was 25 and his mother, Mrs Thomas De Caseborne, was 21. He married Anne De Caseborne in 1397, in Cheriton, Kent, England."},"et":{"Abt 1374–":"umbes 1374–Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1378–1465":"1378–1465","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1399":"139